---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro'
import MapLink from '../../components/MapLink.astro'
---

<Base
  title="Things to Do in Bermuda — The Curated Guide"
  description="A curated guide to the best activities in Bermuda: water sports, cultural sites, cricket, golf, and seasonal events. Honest recommendations, no filler."
>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="hero" style="padding-block: var(--space-16);">
    <div class="hero__inner">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <ol class="breadcrumb" style="justify-content: center; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">
          <li><a href="/Pilot.BM/" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Home</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li><a href="/Pilot.BM/visit" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Visiting</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9);">Things to Do</li>
        </ol>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="hero-title">Things to Do in Bermuda</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        Water, history, sport, and culture — all within 21 square miles.
        A curated guide to spending your time well, without the padded resort itinerary.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container" style="padding-block: var(--space-12);">
    <div style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">

      <!-- Intro -->
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-lg); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
        Bermuda is small enough to cover in a week and deep enough that you could spend a month
        here without exhausting it. The island rewards visitors who combine beach time with a
        little genuine curiosity — the history, the underwater world, and the local sporting culture
        are all worth your attention. What follows is the honest version of the activity list, not
        the one handed to you on a cruise ship dock.
      </p>

      <!-- Water Activities -->
      <section style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">On and under the water</h2>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-anchor" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Top pick</span>
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">Helmet diving</h3>
          <p>
            Helmet diving is Bermuda's most distinctive water activity and one of the few ways to
            walk on the ocean floor without any scuba certification. You wear a large weighted
            helmet that keeps your head dry while you descend to around 10–15 feet on a guided
            reef walk. The guides feed fish by hand and point out coral, sea fans, and the
            occasional moray eel.
          </p>
          <p>
            It sounds gimmicky but is genuinely excellent. Bermuda's reefs are healthy and the
            water clarity is outstanding — visibility regularly exceeds 30 metres. Hartley's
            Helmet Diving operates from Flatts Inlet <MapLink query="Hartley's Helmet Diving, Bermuda" />; expect to pay around $75–95 per person.
            Bermuda claims the practice was invented here, and the conditions justify the claim.
            Not suitable for those with ear problems or significant claustrophobia.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted);">
            Prices correct at time of research — verify before booking.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-featured" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Classic Bermuda</span>
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">Glass-bottom boat tours</h3>
          <p>
            Bermuda has more shipwrecks per square mile than almost anywhere in the world —
            over 300 documented wrecks, most caused by the treacherous reef system surrounding
            the island. A glass-bottom boat tour gives you a clear view of the reefs and, on
            some routes, the wrecks without getting wet. Good for families, non-swimmers, and
            anyone who wants reef geography context before snorkelling independently.
          </p>
          <p>
            Tours depart from both Hamilton Harbour and the Royal Naval Dockyard. Dockyard
            departures tend to cover the more interesting western reef sections. Book a day or
            two ahead in peak season — the better operators fill quickly.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">Cliff jumping at Admiralty House Park <MapLink query="Admiralty House Park, Bermuda" /></h3>
          <p>
            Admiralty House Park in Pembroke Parish is where Bermudians go cliff jumping — not
            the fabricated adventure tourism variety, but proper ledges over clear water used by
            locals for generations. The park has ledges ranging from a few feet to around 20 feet.
            The water is deep and clear. There's no admission charge and no commercial operation.
            You share the space with local teenagers who grew up here and know exactly which
            jumps work.
          </p>
          <p>
            This is one of the genuinely local experiences that costs nothing and appears in almost
            no travel writing. Take Bus 4 from Hamilton (about 10 minutes). The park also has caves
            and tidal pools worth exploring if jumping isn't your thing.
          </p>
          <div class="alert alert-warning" style="margin-top: var(--space-4);">
            <strong>Be sensible:</strong> Check water conditions before jumping. The sea can have
            surge even when it looks calm. Watch others and check the landing zone first. No
            rescue infrastructure is present.
          </div>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">Snorkelling and kayaking</h3>
          <p>
            Tobacco Bay <MapLink query="Tobacco Bay, Bermuda" /> (St. George's) is the best self-guided snorkelling spot on the island —
            sheltered, with dense fish activity around the rock formations. Church Bay <MapLink query="Church Bay, Southampton, Bermuda" /> (Southampton)
            is the other top pick, with good coral structure right off the beach. Gear rental is
            available at Tobacco Bay and Horseshoe Bay <MapLink query="Horseshoe Bay Beach, Bermuda" />; bring your own for anywhere else.
          </p>
          <p>
            For kayaking, the protected waters of Harrington Sound <MapLink query="Harrington Sound, Bermuda" /> in Smith's Parish offer
            extraordinary clarity — you can paddle over reef patches and see down through several
            metres of water. Mangrove Bay <MapLink query="Mangrove Bay, Bermuda" /> in Somerset is a calmer, more sheltered alternative.
            Kayak rentals are available at the Dockyard and through several operators at Shelly Bay.
          </p>
        </article>

        <!-- Affiliate CTA 1 -->
        <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-6); margin-top: var(--space-6);">
          <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-lg); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Book water activities</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4); color: var(--color-ink);">
            Viator aggregates most of the major Bermuda operators in one place — useful for
            comparing times, prices, and reading genuine reviews before you commit.
          </p>
          <a href="/Pilot.BM/go/viator-bermuda" rel="nofollow sponsored" class="btn btn-primary">
            Browse Bermuda Activities on Viator →
          </a>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-xs); color: var(--color-muted); margin-top: var(--space-1);">
            [PLACEHOLDER affiliate link — real ID to be set in affiliate-links.ts after approval]
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Land / Culture -->
      <section style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">Land and culture</h2>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-anchor" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Must-visit</span>
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">Bermuda Underwater Exploration Institute (BUEI) <MapLink query="Bermuda Underwater Exploration Institute, Bermuda" /></h3>
          <p>
            The BUEI on the Hamilton waterfront is one of Bermuda's most underrated attractions.
            The permanent exhibitions cover deep-ocean exploration, Bermuda's maritime history, and
            a remarkable collection related to the island's relationship with the sea — including
            a serious treatment of the wrecks that litter the reef. The mock submersible descent
            is well executed without being theme-park-ish.
          </p>
          <p>
            Spend two to three hours here. It is a particularly good option for a morning before
            beach time or on a day when the weather is unreliable. Entry is around $15 for adults.
            The Harbourfront Restaurant inside is a reasonable lunch option with harbour views.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-featured" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">UNESCO site</span>
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">Fort St. Catherine <MapLink query="Fort St. Catherine, Bermuda" /> and St. George's <MapLink query="Town of St. George's, Bermuda" /></h3>
          <p>
            Fort St. Catherine, on the northeast tip of the island, is the most impressive of
            Bermuda's dozen or so historic forts. Restored well, with exhibits covering Bermuda's
            military history from the early 1600s through World War II, including original Tudor-era
            cannon. The views from the ramparts over the bay toward the open Atlantic are worth
            the trip alone.
          </p>
          <p>
            Combine it with the town of St. George's — the original capital of Bermuda and a UNESCO
            World Heritage Site since 2000. The town is compact, walkable, and genuinely historic
            rather than preserved-for-tourists. St. Peter's Church (1612) is the oldest Anglican
            church in continuous use in the Western Hemisphere. The stocks in the town square are
            still there. St. George's is about 25 minutes from Hamilton by bus or scooter.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">Royal Naval Dockyard <MapLink query="Royal Naval Dockyard, Bermuda" /></h3>
          <p>
            The Dockyard on the western tip of the island was built by the British Navy — using
            enslaved and convict labour from 1809 onward — to service the Atlantic fleet. It's now
            a commercial and cultural complex containing the National Museum of Bermuda <MapLink query="National Museum of Bermuda, Bermuda" /> (the best
            museum on the island), the Bermuda Craft Market, artisan studios, restaurants, and the
            departure point for several boat tours.
          </p>
          <p>
            The National Museum covers Bermuda's history from settlement through the 20th century,
            with a strong maritime collection and an honest treatment of slavery and indenture.
            Budget three to four hours for the full complex. The ferry from Hamilton is the best
            way to arrive — 30 minutes, scenic, no traffic, and the harbour approach to the
            Dockyard is striking.
          </p>
          <p>
            On cruise ship days, the Dockyard is very crowded. Go in the morning before ships arrive
            or on a day without a cruise call if the crowds concern you.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">Hamilton city walk <MapLink query="Hamilton, Bermuda" /></h3>
          <p>
            Hamilton is a small capital — you can walk end to end in about 20 minutes — but it
            rewards a slow look. Front Street along the waterfront has the old colonial facades.
            Walk one block back to Reid Street and Church Street for a less tourist-facing version
            of the city: independent restaurants, local shops, and the covered Washington Mall arcade.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Bermuda Cathedral <MapLink query="Bermuda Cathedral, Bermuda" /> (Cathedral of the Most Holy Trinity) on Church Street is open to
            visitors. The City Hall and Arts Centre <MapLink query="City Hall and Arts Centre, Bermuda" /> on Victoria Street holds rotating exhibitions
            by local artists and is free. Sessions House <MapLink query="Sessions House, Bermuda" />, the Parliament building on Parliament
            Street, is open to the public when in session.
          </p>
          <p>
            Bermuda's architecture is distinctive — white-painted limestone with the characteristic
            stepped white roofs designed to channel rainfall into underground tanks, which are the
            island's primary freshwater source. Worth understanding before you photograph it.
          </p>
        </article>
      </section>

      <!-- Sport -->
      <section style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">Sport</h2>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-anchor" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">National event</span>
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">Cup Match cricket</h3>
          <p>
            <strong>For visitors from the US who aren't familiar with cricket:</strong> Cup Match is
            a two-day cricket match played every year at the end of July or start of August — a
            public holiday in Bermuda. Somerset Cricket Club plays St. George's Cricket Club.
            It has been played annually since 1902.
          </p>
          <p>
            Cricket itself is played with a flat bat on a large oval field. Batsmen try to score
            runs while the fielding side works to dismiss them; teams bat in innings. Think of it
            as baseball's more patient, strategic cousin — played over two full days with no set
            clock. The format means a match can end in a draw if neither side completes two innings,
            which is a legitimate result.
          </p>
          <p>
            What makes Cup Match significant beyond the sport is the atmosphere. It is the largest
            communal celebration on the island — bands, food stalls, and the traditional Crown and
            Anchor gambling booths (a dice game that is only legal in Bermuda during Cup Match days).
            Bermudians who live abroad return for it. If your dates overlap with late July or early
            August, consider planning around this. Tickets are inexpensive; the experience is not.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">America's Cup legacy</h3>
          <p>
            The 35th America's Cup was held in Bermuda in 2017 on the Great Sound — widely
            considered one of the best-run editions of the race in its history. The island's
            sheltered western waters were ideal for the foiling AC50 catamarans, and the race
            brought Bermuda to global attention in a way that conventional tourism advertising
            couldn't match.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Cup is gone but the legacy remains. The Dockyard waterfront was substantially
            improved, sailing participation on the island increased, and several current water
            sports operators trace their setup to the Cup period. The Bermuda Race — the
            prestigious Newport–Bermuda offshore race — still arrives in Hamilton every two
            years (even years), with Race Week bringing a significant influx of sailors to
            the island. Regattas and sailing events fill the summer schedule; check the Royal
            Bermuda Yacht Club calendar if sailing is part of your trip.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
          <h3 style="margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);">Golf</h3>
          <p>
            Bermuda has eight golf courses for an island of 21 square miles — a concentration that
            reflects both the island's British heritage and the demands of its upscale visitor base.
            The two courses worth travelling for are distinct in character.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Port Royal Golf Course</strong> <MapLink query="Port Royal Golf Course, Bermuda" /> (Southampton) is the public-access option and
            consistently rated among the best public courses in the world. Redesigned by Roger
            Rulewich and reopened in 2009, it sits on the south shore with ocean views on several
            holes — the 16th hole, perched above the water, is one of the most photographed in golf.
            Green fees are meaningful by US standards but the quality justifies them.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Mid Ocean Club</strong> <MapLink query="Mid Ocean Club, Bermuda" /> (Tucker's Town) is private and requires a member
            introduction. Designed by Charles Blair Macdonald in 1921, it is by any measure one
            of the great traditional courses in the world. If you have the connection, don't pass
            it up. If you don't, Port Royal is a genuine substitute, not a consolation.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted);">
            Green fees correct at time of research — verify directly with each club before booking.
          </p>
        </article>
      </section>

      <!-- Seasonal -->
      <section style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">Seasonal highlights</h2>

        <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-5); margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
          <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-lg); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Bermuda Heroes Weekend (June)</h3>
          <p style="margin: 0;">
            A multi-day Caribbean carnival celebration in mid-June, built around soca music,
            elaborate costumes, and road marches. The Road Parade closes Hamilton's streets.
            It has grown significantly in recent years and now draws visitors specifically for
            the festival. Hotels book out for this weekend — if your trip overlaps with it,
            plan accommodation at least three to four months ahead.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-5); margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
          <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-lg); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Gombey dancers</h3>
          <p style="margin: 0;">
            The Gombeys are Bermuda's signature folk performance tradition — dancers in elaborate
            feathered costumes with drums, whistles, and whips, performing a style that blends West
            African, Caribbean, Native American, and British colonial influences. The tradition has
            been practised continuously since at least the early 19th century. Performances occur at
            public events throughout the year, concentrated around Cup Match, Heritage Month (May),
            and the summer tourist season. If you see a crowd gathering on a Hamilton street corner,
            it is probably Gombeys.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-5); margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
          <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-lg); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Christmas Boat Parade (December)</h3>
          <p style="margin: 0;">
            Every December, Hamilton Harbour hosts the Christmas Boat Parade — decorated and
            illuminated boats parading past the Hamilton waterfront on a Friday evening. It is an
            unaffected local tradition that happens to be genuinely beautiful on a clear winter night.
            Arrive early for a good spot on Front Street. Dress for December in Bermuda: evenings
            run 15–18°C (59–65°F) — not cold by northern standards, but not tropical.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Affiliate CTA 2 -->
      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-lg); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Browse guided tours</h3>
        <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4); color: var(--color-ink);">
          GetYourGuide has a solid inventory of Bermuda tours — glass-bottom boat, helmet dive,
          historical walking tours, and kayak excursions. Useful for booking ahead, particularly
